If you are defining and calling a function in a single translation unit (&quot;a `.cpp`&quot;), then avoid declaring the function in a header file; unless you want to expose that functionality and have future callers from outside your translation unit.

Furthermore, you should put the function inside an anonymous namespace (or mark it `static`), so that readers (and the compiler) know that this function is private to the translation unit (internal linkage). This may imply that the function does not even get generated at all (the optimizer may decide to inline all callers).

In other words, do:

    namespace {
        void foo() {
            // ...
        }
    }

See as well https://stackoverflow.com/questions/154469/unnamed-anonymous-namespaces-vs-static-functions and https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4422507/superiority-of-unnamed-namespace-over-static

